    {
      "unresolved": true,
      "key": {
        "uuid": "25dd5021_bfa85cdb",
        "filename": "resultdb/internal/services/deadlineenforcer/deadline_enforcer.go",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 74,
      "author": {
        "id": 1114919
      },
      "writtenOn": "2021-05-06T09:13:01Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Sorry, I have no sense if 167 QPS is enough or not.\nPersonally, if I had to convince myself that 100 per shard per minute is enough,\nI\u0027d need to ascertain that either:\n  * ResultDB/Spanner won\u0027t ever sustain creation of \u003e100 Invocations per shard per minute, even when its user misbehaves.\n  * OR, maybe we don\u0027t care if there is a large backlog?\n  * OR, maybe we do care, but we have trooper alert, and so we\u0027ll page a trooper to somehow fix the problem by hand.\n\nHowever, in this case, I think it\u0027s easy to make more scalable code by looping iff number of rows purged equals the limit, e.g. smth like this:\n\nenforceOneShard:\n  const limit \u003d 100\n  for {\n    switch cnt, err :\u003d enforce(ctx, shard, limit);{\n    case err !\u003d nil:\n      return err\n    case cnt \u003c limit:\n      return nil // all done\n    }\n  }\n\n\nIf you adopt this, then you can, in fact, lower the limit to say ~10 and keep a \"large\" transaction as you\u0027ve already coded (see comment thread below).\n\nWDYT?",
      "parentUuid": "85464aa8_7181c92c",
